<LEADPARA>  If the fact that 223 players are making $1 million or more this year -- 32 at
$3 million or more -- is not enough of an economically mind-boggling barometer
of the escalation of baseball salaries, consider these developments:;    Nine
teams have an average salary of more than $1 million, dividing total payroll
by the number of players.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  OPENING-DAY SALARIES SHOOT UP 53 PERCENT
TO AVERAGE OF $890,844  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Complete salary list will appear in Sunday's Mercury News.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     According to figures compiled by the New York Times from contract data
obtained from management and player sources, the average opening-day major
league salary for all players (708 total) is $890,844, an astonishing 53
percent more than last year's opening-day average.;    In previous years, no
individual team's average salary ever reached this year's major league average
salary. The record for a team average was set by the New York Mets in 1989 at
$865,741.;    The A's, with a record $36.4 million payroll and 14 of their 27
players receiving $1 million or more, have the highest team average,
$1,349,352.;    The Giants rose from 12th to sixth on the list at $1,117,619.;
   The Houston Astros are at the other end of the salary standings with an
average of $487,090.;    The five members of the A's who are signed for $3
million or more -- total $16.7 million -- make more than the entire payrolls
of Houston, Baltimore or Seattle. Add Mark McGwire, and the $19.55 million
total is higher than the payroll of those three teams plus Cleveland and the
Chicago White Sox.;    Then throw in Dave Henderson, and the $22.15 million
total is higher than the payrolls of those five clubs plus Texas, Montreal,
Philadelphia, St. Louis, Atlanta and San Diego, or 11 of the other 25 clubs.; 
  The overall increase is dramatic even by baseball's standards. The largest
previous percentage jump was 47.7 percent in 1977, the first year following
free agency. Last season, salaries increased 20.2 percent, according to
figures compiled by the Players Association.;    "Obviously, we think this is
a problem," said Chuck O'Conner, the head of the owners' Player Relations
Committee. "I don't think you can look at this and say this is a situation
that's going to stabilize itself. It's not.";    If all this makes you think
baseball players are paid too much, you aren't alone.;    According to last
week's New York Times/CBS News Poll, those surveyed said by more than a
three-to-one margin (71 percent to 19 percent) that the typical player is paid
too much rather than just the right amount.;    Only 1 percent thought the
typical player is paid too little.  </TEXT>
