<HL> Baseball Team Owners, Free Agents Face a Tough Call
---
Arbitrator to Rule Fair or Foul on
Lack of Interest in Bids for Players
---
By Hal Lancaster
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 08/21/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> LABOR </IN>
<TEXT>
   On Aug. 31, an arbitrator will hand down a ruling that could eventually tilt the economic balance of power in baseball and other professional team sports. 

   Arbitrator Thomas Roberts will decide whether the owners of the 26 major league baseball teams conspired after the 1985 season to prevent players from marketing their services freely, in violation of the collective bargaining agreement that governs the sport's labor relations. 

   If the players win, it could cost the owners plenty. 
If the owners win, it would strengthen their ability to control salaries and render meaningless the concept of free agency -- which lets athletes with six years of major-league experience offer their services to the highest bidder when their contracts expire. 

   The decision could spark litigation by either side, and the whole mess may fester until 1989, when owners and players thrash out a new pact in what promises to be bitter negotiations. 

   After 32 hearing days spread over the past year and 6,000 pages of testimony, many in professional sports are anxiously awaiting the ruling. 
The National Football League and the National Basketball Association are conducting tough labor negotiations in which free agency is a major sticking point. 
They have discouraged it thus far by allowing players' old teams to keep them by matching rival bids. 

   Mr. Roberts's decision probably won't provide an instant resolution, but it should set the tone for future battles. 

   "It's the most important decision since the Messersmith-McNally case," says Randal Hendricks, a Houston lawyer and agent, referring to the 1975 grievances by Los Angeles Dodgers pitcher Andy Messersmith and Baltimore Orioles pitcher Dave McNally that led to free agency in 1976. 
It has been a bitter issue ever since. 

   After baseball owners opened up the market and bid feverishly for players, the average salary boomed to $412,520 from $51,501 in 1976. 
Owners now are howling about unprecedented losses that they say jeopardize the game's economic stability. 

   After the 1985 season, the free-agent market closed up like a clam. 
In the past two off-seasons, only two top-quality free agents changed uniforms. 
Andre Dawson, who left the Montreal Expos for the Chicago Cubs, and Lance Parrish, who went to the Philadelphia Phillies from the Detroit Tigers, accepted contracts that offered less than their original teams did. 

   Meanwhile, Detroit's Kirk Gibson, an ascendant young slugger, and Jack Morris, the winningest pitcher of the 1980s, and Montreal's Tim Raines, last year's National League batting champion, didn't receive offers exceeding their teams' bids. 
Bob Horner of the Atlanta Braves fled to Japan when nobody met his price. 

   Agents and union leaders claimed conspiracy was afoot. 
They filed one grievance on behalf of those who pursued free agency after the 1985 season, and another for the 1986 group. 
The alleged conspiracy, the union and agents claim, has been led by Peter Ueberroth, the economy-minded commissioner who came to baseball in 1984 after transforming the Olympic Games from a big money loser into a model of sports marketing. 

   After Mr. Ueberroth's arrival, coincidence piled upon coincidence. 

   All 26 teams decided they could get by with 24 players, instead of the 25 allowed. 
All 26 decided that player contracts beyond three years were counterproductive. 
And all 26 determined to end their pursuit of free agents and concentrate on developing minor-league prospects. 

   Were the decisions made by each team as "an individual matter" for "its own benefit," as required in the labor pact? 
For a fractious lot, such unanimity seemed far-fetched. 

   What about meetings where Mr. Ueberroth lectured owners on the fiscal foolishness of high-priced free agents? 
What about reports prepared by the owners' Player Relations Council that purported to show that the big-bucks, long-term contracts that came with the free-agent frenzy led to poor performance and wasted money? 
Is that proof of a conspiracy? 

   The commissioner's office has denied any collusion, but Mr. Hendricks said, "It's obvious there is tremendous peer-group pressures among owners and a clearinghouse being run out of league headquarters in New York." 

   If the owners were playing fair, says Don Fehr, executive director of the players union, there would be a market. 
"Even if prices fell, you would have competition at the market price," he reasons. 
"Nobody wanted Jack Morris for $8.50, either." 

   Barry Rona, executive director of the Player Relations Council, says owners have every right to decide against bidding for costly free agents and to discuss issues of mutual economic interest. 
That, he says, is all the teams have done. 

   "If Ford announces a price increase and General Motors thinks it's stupid, they have a right to say so," he said. 

   Mr. Roberts must decide which side is interpreting the collective bargaining agreement correctly, as George Nicolau must do on the second grievance. 

   Which brings up another complication: Mr. Nicolau inherited his grievance when owners fired Mr. Roberts in the midst of last summer's hearings. 
Mr. Rona says Mr. Roberts was fired because owners were outraged over a ruling in which he voided drug-testing clauses in contracts. 
Mr. Fehr says it was a stall tactic. 

   Yet another arbitrator ruled that Mr. Roberts couldn't be removed until he completed his present slate of grievances. 
Having started in 1974, he remains baseball's most senior salary arbitrator. 

   About a week's worth of testimony has been heard in the second arbitration case, with hearings scheduled to resume Monday. 
To many, that case is stronger, because of the higher quality of available free agents. 

   Also, "none of the 1985 free agents played out the string," says Robert Berry, a Boston University sports-law specialist. 
They signed before Jan. 8, 1986, after which their old team wouldn't have been allowed to re-sign them until May 1, almost a month into the season. 
That was designed to encourage rival offers, but several 1986 free agents went through the barrier and still struck out. 

   No one is betting on the outcome of the cases, but both sides are predicting victory. 
If players prevail, baseball insiders and legal specialists expect Mr. Roberts to order salary arbitration to determine how much the affected players were damaged by the collusion. 

   "One way or another, you have to come up with a big pile of money," says Jan Stiglitz, associate dean of the California Western School of Law in San Diego and a labor and sports specialist. 
"If the owners are burned enough by the amount, the market may open up." 

   But Tom Reich, an agent for 80 major leaguers, including Mr. Raines, says bringing players up to market value doesn't constitute enough of an economic sanction to worry owners. 

   "They would be afraid of a federal court action seeking $1 billion." 
He expects a "great wave of litigation" for damages, if the ruling is in the players' favor. 

   Mr. Rona says Mr. Roberts could prohibit the Player Relations Council from disclosing details of one team's offer to another team. 
Does Mr. Rona offer such services presently? 

   "Not as a course of action, generally, but I usually know and if someone were to ask me, I would have no hesitation in telling them," he said. 

   Many fear that an effective remedy doesn't exist. 
"There's not much he (Mr. Roberts) can do to compel owners to bid," says Gary Roberts, a Tulane University law professor who specializes in sports labor and antitrust law. 

   If the owners win, it "would force a player to stay with his old team on their terms -- a shorter contract with less money," says Mr. Hendricks, the agent. 
"Once they do that, they'll attack us on salary arbitration next." 

   That isn't all, Prof. Berry suggests. 
A management triumph would serve as "an invitation to owners in all sports to use various devices such as this to drastically cut back salaries." 

</TEXT>
