<LEADPARA>  AS FRANK CASHEN recalls it, there used to be a saying among major league
baseball executives. "We said you could take your money down to the corner and
put it into a savings and loan and do better," he said. "With what's happened
to S&amp;L's, I'm not sure you'd do either now.";    In the opinion of the game's
26 general managers, including the New York Mets' Cashen, baseball is headed
for the same fate as the S&amp;L industry. That is, an institution that always
seemed so secure appears headed for a reckoning.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Special Section  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CLOUD OF DOOM CASTS ITS SHADOW  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Baseball '91
See also related baseball professional salary chart on this page.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The salaries of players wondrous and woeful have jumped off the sports
pages in recent months while revenue sources essentially remained the same.
St. Louis pitcher Joe Magrane compiles a 10-17 record, and his salary goes
from $300,000 to $1 million, even though Magrane won't be able to play this
season. Boston's Roger Clemens signs for 50 percent more than the salary of
the A's Dave Stewart, who had been the top-paid pitcher. The examples are
well-documented, and the ramifications are foreboding.;    Several of the
general managers who were surveyed by the Mercury News said it has reached the
point where some teams cannot afford to contend.;    Mike Port of the
California Angels said trading increasingly has been inhibited (as the Giants
discovered in the case of shortstop Jose Uribe) and will be more so this
season. Woody Woodward of Seattle and Larry Doughty of Pittsburgh said they
are unable to pursue "blue-chip" free agents.;    Al Rosen of the Giants said
he expects anywhere from 10 to 15 clubs to lose money this year, and this time
without collusion costs included. The A's payroll has doubled within a year,
making a 17-game winner (Scott Sanderson) unaffordable and making it
increasingly difficult to keep an American League dynasty intact.;    Next TV
contract; won't be in billions; Bill Wood of Houston said it is "a good bet
that we've spent that money from the last TV contract, with halfway to go" --
and CBS, which paid $1.06 billion for four years in the current contract,
seems unlikely to talk in billions again in the 1993 deal.;    A couple of
teams have found it necessary to dump high-salaried veterans without
guaranteed contracts -- Fernando Valenzuela and Pete Incaviglia.;    And most
ominously, there is fear in Pittsburgh that the Pirates, who opened the
century with a string of pennants, will end the century somewhere else.
Doughty said the club "would just have to draw back and allow ourselves to
remain solvent" before that were to happen. Yet, just the thought of two Bucs
franchises in the Tampa, Fla., area is cause for concern, taking away some of
the optimism that always abounds on opening day.;    "It's like walking off a
cliff blindfolded -- you never know which step will take you into the abyss,"
Port said, grimly. "It's a Catch-22, because we have to fulfill our charge to
be competitive, yet possibly take ourselves ever closer to that next step on
the cliff.";    Dal Maxvill of St. Louis calls it a "big flashing beacon," and
baseball is not ignoring it. Management and union agreed on a blue-ribbon
study group that includes former Federal Reserve Board Chairman Paul Volcker,
Rockefeller Foundation Chairman Peter Goldmark of the Rockefeller Foundation,
Cal law professor David Feller, Henry Aaron (not the Hall-of-Fame player) of
the Brookings Institution, Milwaukee Brewers owner Bud Selig and Donald Fehr,
head of the Players Association.;    Commissioner Fay Vincent said during a
spring-training visit to Arizona that he hopes to have substantial data "in
about a year" and then address the major issues.;    "If you see the iceberg
emerging, you will not hit it. Why do we have to wait until we hit it?"
Vincent said. "The group will look at the economics of baseball in its
broadest sense and make recommendations and findings. The thing we need most
is some data, some correlation between what our figures are and what the
Players Association's figures are. One problem we have with the union is
establishing a factual basis for economics. That's why this group was
formed.";    G.M. view clouded;; players ignore storm;  According to Fehr,
"One of the problems with general managers making comments is that it may be
that a G.M. only sees a tiny part of the operation. The general manager of the
White Sox doesn't know anything about the real estate side. And it's all tied
up together. The general manager of the Braves may not know very much about
how much TBS is making. You've got to correlate all this data and try to make
sense of it.";    Dave Anderson, the Giants' co-player representative and a
four-year rep while with Los Angeles, said players do not see the storm clouds
that the general managers speak about.;    "Our whole complaint (during last
year's labor standoff) was that there was no telltale sign of problems in
baseball," he said. "Teams were making money. Salaries basically stayed the
same for a few years. If we have evidence of financial problems in the game,
the Players Association will try to work with management as much as it can.
Until that happens, we feel the system is working pretty good. There's no
question that this is a good time to play baseball.";    The average salary is
about $800,000 this season. More than 40 players make at least $3 million a
year, as Rickey Henderson reminds us. Each G.M. winces at each trend-setting
contract, such as Rosen's November free-agent signing of Bud Black (four
years, $10 million), and each G.M. says it is a matter of playing by the
rules.;    Some teams are choosing not to play by the rules, though. St. Louis
and Houston, two frequent contenders in the 1980s, let their big free agents
walk and chose to rebuild.;    "Not to say a Houston or a St. Louis won't
shock somebody," said Montreal G.M. David Dombrowski, "but they're not taking
the approach it takes to win.";    Added Lee Thomas of Philadelphia: "Once
clubs find out they're not going to be in a race, they're going to try to get
out from under. Some already can't afford to win. I don't like to see that
happen to this game. A lot of us are trying to screw it up.";    From a fan's
view, Chicago G.M. Jim Frey said, one noticeable change this year will be the
lack of trades for middle-level players.;    "I mean veteran, bench players,"
he said. "Not long ago, there were times when I'd look across the field and
see (Lou) Piniella and Jim Spencer and (Bob) Watson sitting on the bench,
waiting to pinch hit. You can't afford to have players at that level now. I
think all of us are trying to concentrate on younger players whenever
possible.";    One concern to most everyone, even to some players, is the
disparity between large and small markets.;    Small markets can't; compete
with giants;  Although even they are prohibiting contract extensions during
this uncertainty, the Los Angeles Dodgers have the financial wherewithal to
pay a Darryl Strawberry what he wants. Their local TV deal pays well. But how
do you compete in Cleveland or Seattle or any of a number of smaller cities?
You had better have a plentiful farm system, and even then you can only keep
talent for so long.;    "If we had kept 11 players from our (world
championship) '87 team that won 85 games in a division not as strong as it is
today, those players would be worth $23.5 million now," Minnesota G.M. Andy
MacPhail said. "No way we can do that." He was referring to Tom Brunansky,
Kirby Puckett, Dan Gladden, Greg Gagne, Gary Gaetti, Kent Hrbek, Gene Larkin,
Bert Blyleven, Jeff Reardon, Juan Berenguer and Frank Viola. Seven are gone.; 
  "You have teams that bring in $32 million and teams that bring in $100
million, and yet our expenses are interrelated," added MacPhail, who
nevertheless signed veteran pitcher Jack Morris to a deal that could be worth
up to $11 million over three years. "I think people understand that it's not
going to last this way. We have been undergoing a process of educating the
fans to that effect. It's just going to be a matter of two or three years, if
not sooner, that we have some traumatic event.";    What is that traumatic
event? When Vincent was asked for his worst-case scenario, he replied, "I
learned a long time ago, the worst case never happens. We live our lives in
the gray, never in the black.";    Most of the general managers were less
optimistic. Most said they feared a franchise "going belly-up" and trying to
find a buyer. The Houston Astros, who were bankrupt once before, have been for
sale the past winter, and it has not been easy for John McMullen to find a
suitable taker.;    "When you don't have a handle on your expenses, and you
know pretty much what your revenue streams are, you've got a real problem,"
Rosen said. "And there might someday be a club that can't afford this anymore.
Then what if you can't find a buyer?;    "Sure, there might be owners who, in
order to massage their egos, want to own a major league team, and they may be
willing to lose $3, 4, 5 million a year, but no one knows what the topside is
as salaries continue to escalate. You may be talking about $20 million losses.
Or $25 million. Who knows where the salaries are going to go?";    The fans
will howl; at big jump in prices;  National League President Bill White,
during a recent lecture in Chicago, said about the possibility of an owner
declaring bankruptcy: "I don't think that day is far off unless they pass it
on to the fans -- and I don't think they'll stand for $20 to $30 for a
ticket.";    Boston G.M. Lou Gorman said the Red Sox "appeal to the working
class. The guy who's got a family wants to spend $8 or $9 a ticket, buy a hot
dog and a drink, and not go broke. Our ticket prices have stayed reasonably
the same over the last seven years, and our payroll has gone from $7 million
to $34 million in that time.";    So why did Gorman make Clemens, a player who
performs only every fifth day, the richest player in the game? Cashen, who
then has to negotiate with Dwight Gooden and Viola, calls it "the worst
example I've seen over the years. That's management's fault.";    This is
Gorman's explanation: "He puts people in the ballpark. If we lose him to our
high-school draft (a form of compensation for a lost free agent), they would
have hung me from a flagpole in center field.";    Fehr remains skeptical
about the concern over the disparity in markets.;    "I spent all last
winter," he said, "listening to very nasty complaints about small markets:
'They're terrible, they can't generate enough revenues. We have to have salary
caps. We're going to do this, we're going to do that, and we're going to lock
you out to get it.';    "Now we get to November 1990, and they have to pay
collusion damages, and they owe the players $280 million. They can pay that
any way they wanted to. Do you think they gave Pittsburgh and Milwaukee a
break? Huh-unh. Pittsburgh and Milwaukee were forced by the other clubs to pay
ever last nickel the Dodgers, the Mets and the Yankees do.;    "What that
suggests is that the clubs, overall, don't really have the concern that would
be best for collective bargaining.";    Virtually all of the general managers
agreed that salaries should be somehow tied to performance. That idea was
rejected by the union during the 1990 lockout. The executives said the past
negotiations and holdouts are good reason for it.;    "Now, all you've got to
do is just show up and stay healthy," Frey said. "Performance is just one part
of the equation. You've got to have 25 players, and somebody's got to be in
uniform. As they get their service time, they jump to service levels -- many
times, without good performance.";    Added MacPhail: "The one thing that
ought to be crystal clear now is, it doesn't have a damn thing to do with
money. It's who's making more. Whether we go through some sort of statistical
level that compensates a player for stats, or whether it's a (salary) cap that
a player reaches and tops off and doesn't have to worry about it anymore, I'm
confident baseball will solve its problems.";    Dodgers G.M. Fred Claire said
he hopes all parties in baseball will recognize that "we're just passing
through. We're fortunate to have a hand or a say in what is taking place, and
we should recognize the responsibility we have in every part.";    Atlanta
G.M. John Schuerholz said agents tell him privately "how wacky this baseball
salary business is.";    Texas G.M. Tom Grieve said the fact that the union
agreed to the study-group concept and the group's membership was a sign that
it is interested in cooperating.;    Rosen is not buying it.;    "Why would a
player want to give up what he's got?" he asked. "Why would (Giants catcher)
Steve Decker, who's a budding young star, first year in the league, want to do
something that would keep him from making the kind of money that some of his
predecessors are making?;    What goes up; must come down;  "And that's a
constituency of the Players Association. Those fellows can't act without the
players voting. Now how are you going to get your message across to the
players? Those players don't care. . . . The only way they're going to give it
up is kicking and screaming to the gas chamber.;    "But," he added, "one
thing I've learned from life is that nothing goes (only) up. And it returns to
Earth a hell of a lot faster. Galileo proved that.";    No one can predict
what the descent will be in baseball. Much depends on what money CBS will
offer in 1993. A CBS Sports spokesman said the network "would rather not
speculate on what may happen in the future," and Vincent said, "I'm not that
smart. I don't know how anybody can predict something two years off. Network
TV is a complicated industry.";    Gorman said of the next TV contract: "The
money won't be the same. CBS has already asked baseball to pay back $200
million.";    In the meantime, the Giants' Anderson said, players will enjoy
their prosperity and wait for the study group to show any cause for concern.
In the meantime, Wood said, he sees "at least a couple of years of serious
struggle for the bottom-tiered clubs.";    In the meantime, baseball will
begin again Monday, including the traditional opener at Cincinnati's
Riverfront Stadium. Reds G.M. Bob Quinn is optimistic about his
defending-champion team, but not about the major leagues' future.;   
"Certainly there's going to have to be some realism that sets in," he said.
"Right now we're in a fairy tale, a fantasy world when it comes to contract
negotiations. You're fast hitting a point where something dire will come of
it."  </TEXT>
