<DESCRIPT>  HIGH-SCHOOL; BASEBALL; PROFESSIONAL; DRAFT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  One day he has it all, or as much as a high school baseball player could want:
respect, popularity and star status among his peers.;    Then -- only if he is
among the truly fortunate -- he loses it all and finds himself on the bottom
rung of professional baseball's ladder. He begins his career on a major league
team's rookie squad.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MILES FROM HOME
FOLLOWING THE LONG ROAD TO MAJORS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  High School Report
See related story page 7C of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Rookie ball is the beginning of the long road to major league baseball that
most players never finish.;    "Ninety-five percent of them fail," said Ed
Sprague Sr., a Baltimore Orioles scout who has seen his share of high school
stars fade.;    The trials of those carefully selected few who get to start
that infrequently finished trek often go unnoticed. Once hometown favorites,
they become anonymous after signing contracts and starting their assignments
in faraway towns.;    How they handle the adjustment goes a long way in
determining how far down that road to the majors they will get, baseball
officials say.;    Baltimore's Scott Miley, Montreal's Duane Ashley and
Cleveland's Jason Hardtke are the only high school players from Santa Clara
and southern Alameda counties drafted in the last two years who signed minor
league contracts.;    Miley, who starred as a center fielder at Mission San
Jose, was taken in the 14th round by the Orioles in last year's draft. Ashley,
a former Yerba Buena pitcher, went to the Expos in the 25th round of the '89
draft. Hardtke, who was named Mercury News co-player of the year after his
senior season as a shortstop at Leland, was chosen by the Indians in the third
round of the '90 draft.;    Hardtke has reached Cleveland's Class A squad, the
Columbus (Ga.) Indians, after first being assigned to rookie ball in
Burlington, N.C.;    After 32 games and 122 at-bats, Hardtke was struggling
with a .238 batting average and nine errors.;    But the biggest challenge, he
said, is not to finish the season at .400; it's just to finish the 144-game
season.;    Hardtke said rookie ball helped him prepare for that. He learned
how to manage on the $850 per month rookies are typically paid. He learned how
to choose and set up his own apartment. And he learned to deal with being
3,000 miles away from his family in Almaden Valley.;    "It was all new to
me," Hardtke said, "added pressure.";    The Indians, like other big-league
organizations, tried to ease Hardtke's adjustment by providing some apartments
to choose from.;    "(Major league organizations) all try to do as much as
they can to make it easier," Columbus Manager Mike Brown said. "This is the
real world, and, to make things easier, that allows them to concentrate on
what they're here for.";    A tight schedule;  In addition to providing a
choice of apartments, big-league organizations set a tight schedule for
rookies to adhere to.;    For example, at Pittsburgh's spring-training
facility in Bradenton, Fla., Expos, Pirates and Atlanta Braves rookies all
live and train at the same facility.;    Breakfast is early, from 7:30 to 8:30
a.m., and dinner is from 5 to 6 p.m. There are practices and games six days a
week. The season lasts for three months.;    After a short break, successful
rookies move on to the Class A "short season," which lasts from June to
September. Those who show promise there are promoted to "long season" Class A,
where the season is 144 games long.;    Dave Tomlin, a former major league
pitcher who is now the pitching coach of the Bradenton Expos, said the rookie
schedule is tough but not unmanageable.;    "Once they get in the routine,
it's not that bad," Tomlin said. "If you want to play baseball, it's not that
bad. If you don't, then it's bad.";    And the bat boy is . . .; Tomlin said
rookie ball provides its own unique ways of disciplining players who won't
conform.;    "We have very few fans at our games," Tomlin explained. "It's not
like the organization is going to shell out money for bat boys. That's the job
the players hate most. If a guy gives me some lip, I'll just say, 'Hey, you
want to be bat boy tomorrow?' Right then, he shuts up.";    Miley, who is
being moved to first base from the outfield, said some rookies don't adapt
quickly.;    "A lot of kids out here are kind of lost," he said. "I really
didn't get lost, because this is what I really want to do.";    Sprague said
many players are not mature enough to make it on their own.;    "A lot of kids
just quit because they don't like being away," he said. "Soon as they get out
of the house, they can't handle it without Mom or Dad around.";    Sprague
added that major league clubs believe the vast majority of players should go
through rookie ball to better prepare them for the big leagues. Today's high
salaries leave little room for players who make it to the big leagues before
they are ready, he said.;    Still, that knowledge doesn't make rookie ball
any easier. Baseball officials say only those whose love for the game equals
their talent will make it.;    Hardtke said rookie ball didn't change his
feelings for the game.;    "I still love the game," he said. "I love playing
it. I thought I knew everything about the sport, but I got to professional
ball and found out I was wrong."  </TEXT>
