<LEADPARA>  Roger Clemens of the Boston Red Sox more than salvaged what had been a stormy
off-season Friday, becoming baseball's highest-paid player.;    The
28-year-old right-handed pitcher agreed to a five-year contract with an
average salary of $5.38 million, which surpasses the previous high, Jose
Canseco's $4.7 million per year for five years with the A's, signed June 27,
1990.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CLEMENS TOPS SALARY LIST  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Chart attached to end of article  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Canseco and another outfielder, Darryl Strawberry of the Los Angeles
Dodgers ($4.05 million), had been the only players averaging $4 million or
more.;    "Roger made his decision a long time ago that Boston is one of the
four great cities to play baseball in," said Randy Hendricks, one of two
agents who helped Clemens land the contract. "He was up for the challenge.
It's the challenge of getting along with the media, the fans and pitching the
Red Sox to their first world championship in 72 years that keeps Roger going.
It gives him the drive to succeed.";    That drive to succeed, which helped
Clemens to a 21-6 record in 1990, got Clemens in trouble in the fourth game of
the American League playoffs last year in Oakland. He was ejected from Game 4
during a run-in with umpire Terry Cooney as the A's completed a sweep of the
Red Sox. He was fined $10,000 and faces a five-game suspension this season.
Clemens' off-field problems include a Feb. 20 arraignment hearing in Houston
on charges of aggravated assault on a Houston police officer as a result of an
early morning incident at Bayou Mama's nightclub Jan. 19.;    Despite those
problems, Red Sox General Manager Lou Gorman had predicted late last week the
contract would be agreed upon by this week.;    "I think the club had a
realistic view of how much it would take to sign Roger from the beginning,"
Gorman said. "We recognized that we were dealing with the best pitcher in
baseball. We didn't take his off-field problems into consideration seriously,
because we feel they will get resolved and Roger performs for us on the field
and donates much of his time to charitable causes in the area.";    Clemens,
who earns $2.5 million this season, the final year of his current three-year,
$7.5 million deal, received a $621,000 signing bonus that will be paid when he
officially signs. In 1992, Clemens will earn $4.4 million, followed by $4.5
million in 1993, $5 million in 1994 and $5.5 million in 1995. Clemens' option
year calls for $6 million in 1996. But the Red Sox can buy out his contract
for $1.5 million in '96.;    The Red Sox can exercise the '96 option after the
1991 or 1992 season at $5.5 million. If they wait until after 1993, the salary
would rise to $5.8 million. From the 1994 season on, the option shifts from
the team to Clemens, whose salary at that point would be $6 million.;    The
Red Sox have gone on a winter-long spending spree. They have committed more
than $73.2 million over the next five years to six major signings this
winter.;    Clemens' contract marked another step in the vast escalation of
salaries over the past 16 months. Minnesota outfielder Kirby Puckett became
the first $3 million-a-year player on Nov. 22, 1989, and Clemens became the
34th to reach that level.;    Nolan Ryan got the first $1 million-a-year
contract in November 1979, and George Foster became the first $2 million
player in February 1982.;    When told of Clemens' contract, Baltimore Orioles
General Manager Rollie Hemond, whose team payroll for last year and this year
will be about $5 million short of Clemens' contract, said, "I guess I'm at a
loss for words. I can think back to my Milwaukee days when Warren Spahn made
$60,000 after winning 20 just about every year. (John) Quinn would say, 'Well,
