<HEADLINE>  BLACK BASEBALL SPANNED ALMOST A CENTURY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Field of Dreams
See related articles on page 1C and 4C
Additional information attached to end of article  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Even an all-black team wouldn't hesitate to adopt a nickname such as Grays,
Clowns, X-Giants or Black Yankees.;    It was the time of black baseball in
America -- the Negro leagues and barnstorming teams -- and it lasted from the
1860s, when the Civil War freed the slaves, until the 1960s, when the
civil-rights movement reached its zenith.;    The Negro leagues were the
product of a society not comfortable with itself, and they produced some
extraordinary ballplayers.;    After 1947, when Jackie Robinson became the
first black player in the major leagues, a few of his Negro league
contemporaries also were able to sign on with big league teams. Only a handful
were recognized by the Baseball Hall of Fame.;    It took World War II and the
racial rantings of Adolf Hitler to focus America's attention on its own racial
hypocrisy, according to historian Jules Tygiel of San Francisco State, whose
best-known baseball work is "Baseball's Great Experiment -- Jackie Robinson
and his Legacy.";    Tygiel -- a historian by profession, a baseball historian
by avocation -- has traced evidence of black baseball players to before the
Civil War in an article he wrote for the encyclopedia "Total Baseball," but he
found the first evidence of teams in Northern cities in 1867 when the Brooklyn
Uniques played the Philadelphia Excelsiors in what was billed as the
"championship of colored clubs.";    The same year, the Philadelphia Pythians,
another black club, sent a representative to the organizational meeting of the
National Association of Base Ball Players, which became the first professional
baseball league, according to David Q. Voight's baseball history in "Total
Baseball.";    The Pythians were barred because the association said "if
colored clubs were admitted there would be in all probability some division of
feeling, whereas, by excluding them no injury could result to anyone.";   
That didn't mean professional baseball was an entirely segregated game.;   
All through baseball history there were games, mainly exhibition contests,
played between all-white and all-black teams. And there were integrated teams
in the International Association, a minor league with teams in the northern
United States and Canada as late as 1898.;    A black catcher, Moses Fleetwood
Walker, and his brother Welday helped organize an integrated team at Oberlin
College in 1881, and Fleet Walker later played two seasons for the University
of Michigan.;    Walker, not Jackie Robinson, was the first black major
leaguer when he joined Toledo of the American Association in 1884, according
to Tygiel.;    But black players were gradually driven out of mainstream
professional baseball through the rejection of teammates, ugly incidents and
finally outright banning.;    That was the situation that prompted the
formation of the first of a series of Negro leagues that, at times, paid wages
that topped those of the major leagues.;    The first truly successful league
was the Negro National League founded in 1919, by Rube Foster, a
player-turned-executive. Foster's league spawned others such as the Eastern
Colored League.;    Teams and leagues tended toward financial instability,
however, and the best players jumped from team to team and league to league
without penalty. The strongest black teams, such as the Kansas City Monarchs
and Homestead Grays (Pittsburgh), existed outside formal leagues at times,
barnstorming across the country playing league teams, white teams and any
other opponents that could draw paying crowds.;    Negro league teams made
important contributions to the sport. The Monarchs, one of the longest-lived
and most successful clubs, had a portable lighting system built in 1929, so
they could play as many as three games a day. They played the first night
professional baseball game in 1930, according to Tygiel.;    Tygiel said
seasons ran 200 or more games, many of them exhibitions that didn't count in
league standings. Teams often played their weekend games in major league
parks, welcomed by teams such as the Yankees looking for rental revenue on
days they were on the road.;    In the 1930s and '40s, Negro league teams
frequently played exhibitions against teams of major league all-stars to
sellout crowds of black and white fans. Tygiel's research of interracial games
in the 1930s indicates Negro league teams won two-thirds of the games.;   
Jackie Robinson's acceptance in the major leagues spelled the end of the Negro
leagues, although their death was slow. It wasn't until 1959, 12 years after
Jackie Robinson first played for the Brooklyn Dodgers, that the Boston Red Sox
ended the all-white era of the major leagues. The Red Sox were the last team
to integrate their roster.;    The Negro American League shrank from 10 teams
in 1948 to four by 1953. Barnstorming black teams continued to hang on. Kansas
City's last East-West All Star Game between black teams was played in 1963.
The Monarchs folded in 1964.;  THE NEGRO LEAGUES; The four most successful
formal leagues during baseball's segregated era (many other all-black pro
