<TEXT>
   I wish I could remember who -- wrote, "There's no sport righter than a sportswriter." 
It's a cute line, but untrue. 
In fact, there's no sport righter than a baseball commissioner. 

   If you doubt that, pick up "Hardball: The Education of a Baseball Commissioner" (Times Books, 453 pages, $19.95) by Bowie Kuhn. 
In 15 years as occupant of the august post (1969-84), Mr. Kuhn never made a bum decision. 
Who says so? 
Why, Mr. Kuhn, of course. 

   That never-wrong posture was easily the most irritating aspect of lawyer Kuhn's tenure as Major League baseball's chief executive. 
In private conversation, he could be canny, pleasant and witty, and display the sort of self-deprecating humor that is rare among pooh-bahs of sport or other fields. 
The public man, however, was capable of carrying out the most blatant nonsense with an air of perfect rectitude. 
Who but Bowie Kuhn, for instance, could sit serenely outdoors in bone-chilling cold at one of the first World Series night games (a Kuhn innovation!) wearing just a business suit, while all about him huddled in greatcoats? 

   "Hardball" is, in part, a conference-room history of the Kuhn years in Major League baseball. 
On this level it succeeds, although I suspect it contains more information than most people want to know about what went on behind closed doors when club owners lit their big cigars. 

   The book also is a payback for a lengthy list of people whom Mr. Kuhn believes did him -- and the National Pastime -- wrong during his regime. 
It is not surprising that his No. 1 bad guy is Marvin Miller, who, as head of the player's union, was his leading public antagonist. 

   What is surprising is the lack of grace (sportsmanship?) with which Mr. Kuhn appraises his foe. 
According to Mr. Kuhn, Mr. Miller was "pedantic, fussy over details and unwilling to deal straightforwardly with issues." 
He was "sly . . . a mean-spirited badger" and -- worst of all -- "not a fan" (gasp!). 

   Most astonishingly, he describes the man who repeatedly bested his owner-employers in negotiations as "not good at the bargaining table." 
Mr. Kuhn appears not to have read the table on page 169 of his own book, which details a sevenfold increase (to $325,000) in the annual salaries of the Miller-led players between 1976 and 1984. 
Mr. Miller was just lucky, I guess. 

   A similar sourness of grapes mars Mr. Kuhn's version of the overturning of the infamous Reserve Clause, which bound a baseball player to his team without recourse from the time he signed his first professional contract until he was traded or left the game. 
That system fell not because of the law or simple fairness, Mr. Kuhn writes, but because of the "anti-management bias" of Peter Seitz, the arbitrator whose decision began its demise. 

   Mr. Kuhn says he could have negotiated a better free-agent system than the one that emerged following Mr. Seitz's ruling, but he doesn't say what that might have been, or why he didn't propose it when it might have done some good. 

   More entertaining, but no less puzzling, is Mr. Kuhn's account of his battles with Charlie Finley, the profane, cantankerous owner of the Oakland A's during the 1960s and '70s. 
You remember Charlie; he was the guy with the mule, the orange baseball, and all those pennants and World Series titles. 
He had to sell his club after free agency hit and Mr. Kuhn set a $400,000 lid on the price he could get for his stars from other teams before they hit the road on their own. 

   Why $400,000? 
It was the price Mr. Finley had set for the sale of a so-so relief pitcher, and thus was "handy." 
Also, a higher figure would have "undermined public confidence" in club integrity. 
Thus spake Bowie, who, by the way, detested Mr. Finley. 

   Mr. Kuhn goes down the list of his other "controversial" decisions, most of which, he assures us, were arrived at only after Nixonesque agonizing. 
Shopping-center developer Edward DeBartolo was denied the right to buy the Chicago White Sox because he was an out-of-towner and had race-track interests, even though other team owners shared those characteristics and most Chicagoans would have welcomed the infusion of his big bucks. 
Mickey Mantle and Willie Mays couldn't decorate spring-training batting cages because they were casino greeters. 

   An aging Hank Aaron, a swing or two from Babe Ruth's career-home-run record, couldn't be held out of an early season road game so he could break the mark before home fans in Atlanta. 
The "reputation of the game" demanded that he play, ruled Mr. Kuhn. 

   Indeed, the most irksome aspects of this book are Mr. Kuhn's constant references to "public" or "fan" interests to justify his rulings, and his wrapping his decisions in the banner of "baseball" the way others use the flag. 
To hear Mr. Kuhn tell it, arbitrator Seitz's freeing of the players was an offense against "baseball," not just the owners who employed him. 

   In fact, "baseball" has a life in parks and schools all over the world, quite apart from the doings in the Majors. 
At times, it seems to thrive despite, rather than because of, what the big fellas are up to. 

</TEXT>
