<TEXT>
   The professional-football strike, which almost nobody expected and nobody professes to want, is here, and we fans are left with but two alternatives. 
We can sit around gnashing our teeth, or find ways to enjoy our new-found Sunday freedom. 

   Chicago Bears coach Mike Ditka, a blunt but usually sensible man, suggests the latter course. 
"Check out the price of boats," he told the Chicago Tribune. 
"There's a nice lake out there." 
That sounded like good advice even if one isn't fortunate enough to live along the sunny shores of Lake Michigan. 
If nothing else, it's easier on the teeth than gnashing. 

   While we are out sailing, though, we might ponder what the strike is all about, and what it says about the games we love. 
In fact, those questions might consume more than just a Sunday afternoon, because neither admits to an easy answer. 

   To hear both the National Football League players and owners tell it, the strike is about free agency, or the ability of players to perform for teams of their own choosing. 
The players want it because they think it will enrich them. 
The owners oppose it for the same reason. 

   Further examination, however, suggests that things might not be that simple. 
The pro footballers had theoretical free agency for a time as a result of a court decision striking down the so-called Rozelle Rule, which allowed the commissioner to set compensation in player-movement cases. 
But the union bargained it away in return for a union-security clause and other concessions. 

   A modified form of free agency was negotiated in 1977, but just one player has changed uniforms as a result, and you're a real trivia ace if you can name him. 
Owners say that's because the draft-choice compensation they must pay for a free agent is too steep, but another explanation is that they have decided, individually or collectively, not to vie for the available bodies. 

   In a remarkable coincidence, an arbitrator ruled on Monday -- the day before the football strike -- that Major League baseball team owners had violated their labor agreement by colluding to snub free agents in 1985. 
Damages weren't set, however, and a remedy that could aid future free-agent baseballers might be hard to come by. 
Given the football owners' record of bidding restraint, prospects for grafting the laudable institution onto the gridiron sport aren't bright no matter what a contract says. 

   Some players, probably the ones who read the newspapers, have been outspoken in the belief that free agency ain't the be-all and end-all their union makes it out to be. 
"In baseball, you've had superstars like (Detroit Tigers pitcher) Jack Morris out there, and no one bidding on him. 
What makes you think anyone would bid for bums like me?" said David Huffman, a veteran offensive guard for the Minnesota Vikings. 
"I'm more concerned about getting a bigger piece of the pie." 

   So, if you eliminate free agency as the strike's true engine, you've got the normal mix of ingredients in the labor-management stew (wage scales, pensions, injury benefits and the like) and the intangible but nonetheless vital matter of winning or losing. 
Again, the history of labor relations in football is instructive. 
The two sides have reasoned together five times, and the result has been four strikes -- in 1968, '70, '74 and '82 -- in addition to the present one. 
The weight-room adage of "no pain, no gain" seems to apply. 

   The problem from the players' standpoint is that while they've undergone the pain, they haven't realized the gains. 
By most judgments they are 0-5 in their tilts with the owners, and it was mainly the bidding war with the short-lived U.S. Football League, not the fruits of labor negotiations, that boosted the average annual salary in the NFL to about $200,000 from $90,000 in '82. 
And even at that level, football pay lags well behind that of baseball and basketball. 

   Why the football union has failed where other sports unions have succeeded is a matter of surmise. 
Leadership, or the lack of it, certainly has been a factor. 
Suffice it to say that the players' desire to break their long losing streak might well be the overlooked factor in this go-around. 

   By any rational standard, the football strike should be among the least of our concerns, and the usual radio-talk-show rantings shouldn't obscure Joe Fan's short memory. 
Baseball bounced back from its 1981 strike to set attendance records, and the fact that the NFL gate hasn't quite recovered from the 57-day players' walkout of 1982 -- the only one that disrupted regular-season play -- probably has as much to do with high ticket prices and full stadiums in many cities as fan disaffection. 

   Rooting for a team, though, has always been like enjoying a motion picture in that it requires a suspension of disbelief. 
At the movies, you must block from your mind the thought that cameras are grinding a few feet from the actors. 
Wholehearted sports partisanship requires the no-less-difficult conviction that our favorites and their bosses are as devoted as we to the cities they represent and the outcome of the games at hand. 

   In recent years we have witnessed a string of events that have punctured that conviction. 
The floating-franchise phenomenon heads the list, but athlete drug use and recurring labor-management strife are close behind. 
The football owners' insistence that they will field pickup teams if the walkout doesn't end soon would be another, and a grievous one. 
To date, at least, attendance has held up well enough, but sports crowds are less forgiving than they used to be -- more businesslike, if you will. 
As the bonds of allegiance break, we become more like our erstwhile heroes, and their employers. 

   ---
   The sole NFL player to change teams via free agency was defensive back Norm Thompson, who moved from St. Louis to Baltimore in 1977. 

</TEXT>
