<TEXT>
   April 26
   The Parkersburg (W.Va.) News on racism:
   Professional baseball player Jose Canseco's claim he's a victim
of racism should outrage every American. ...
   Canseco plays ... for the Oakland Athletics. After signing a new
contract for the coming year, he had a few words to say to the
press. He was upset the A's didn't agree to pay him more. Canseco
is a Hispanic who came to the United States from Cuba. The reason
he didn't get a better contract is racism, opined Canseco.
   His contract is for $2 million. For one year.
   Various adjectives could be used to describe accurately a $2
million a year contract for a baseball player. ``Racist'' isn't one
of them.
   People who have been victims of racism should be enraged at
Canseco's idiotic, insensitive comment. Leaders of civil rights
groups fighting ... true racism should condemn Canseco for his
egotistical outburst. Baseball fans should display their
displeasure, perhaps by letting A's management know they don't
appreciate Canseco. Such expressions of concern might be
particularly appropriate coming from members of minorities who have
trouble scraping up the increasing price of admission to a
professional game.
   Racism? Hardly. With $2 million to invest and produce enough
income to keep him on easy street for the rest of his life, Canseco
never will experience some of the most difficult aspects of real
racism. That's a shame. It might make him more sensitive to the
plight of people who have real problems instead of imagined ones.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 28
   The World, Coos Bay, Ore., on baseball:
   It's going to be interesting to see whether professional
baseball collapses under its own greed or survives to maintain its
place as America's favorite game of summer.
   Fresh on the heels of the ... strike-lockout this spring comes
news that television viewers across the nation are going to be
short on chances to watch their favorite games this summer. ...
   (T)he Saturday Game of the Week, an American tradition as deep
as hot dogs and Cracker Jacks, is gone. It was murdered in the
crossfire of a corporate bidding shoot-out between NBC and CBS. The
winner, CBS, plans to give sports fans only 16 games this season _
and it might have been only eight if the public hadn't complained.
...
   How long can baseball survive with fans who can only see
occasional games on regular TV or cable TV, or have to shell out
lots of money for a satellite system, or have to find time for
long-distance travel to a game?
   Baseball has been a game of the common man _ a slow summer
respite from the busy American lifestyle. Its history is one of
being open to all; exclusivity has never been a factor.
   But greed seems to be leading baseball astray.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 27
   The Journal Times, Racine, Wis., on the America's Cup:
   Perhaps it was appropriate that the final decision on the winner
of the America's Cup, the Super Bowl of sailing, was made in a
courtroom far removed from the sea.
   It epitomized the fact that the America's Cup has been made a
mockery as a premier sailing event and _ like so many other sports
_ has become primarily a legal exercise.
   For the record, the New York ... Court (of Appeals), sitting in
Albany, awarded the America's Cup to the San Diego Yacht Club, in
effect ruling that the catamaran used in the last races was not an
illegal craft.
   The appeal of the San Diego Yacht Club victory had been filed by
the loser, New Zealand's Mercury Bay Club.
   The race was sailed in September 1988 and the outcome has been
filling lawyers' pockets ever since.
   So San Diego has the cup and we can look forward to another
America's Cup race in 1992. Supposedly, possession of the Cup is
vital to a city because it means millions of dollars in revenue to
the host city during the races.
   But we can't help wondering if the legal skirmishes, and the
ruling which pretty well opens the race to virtually any kind of
vessel, haven't severely tarnished the cup.
   We won't be surprised if, when 1992 comes around, many sailing
enthusiasts simply shrug and say, as we are tempted to, ``who
cares?''
</TEXT>
